column168: LOAD EN ROUTE FROM THE GENERATOR TO THE DISPOSAL SITE.  CONTENTS OF THE VAN TRAILER WERE PLASTIC DRUMS ON PALLETS WHICH WERE BANDED WITH PLASTIC SHRINK-WRAP TYPE MATERIAL THE LOAD WAS SECURED WITH LOAD LOCKS. VEHICLE IN FRONT OF THE BEALINE TRUCK SUDDENLY, WITHOUT WARNING BRAKED TO STOP.  BEALINE DRIVER HAD TO INITIATE EMERGENCY BRAKING TO AVOID COLLISION. THE CONTENTS OF THE VAN SHIFTED VIOLENTLY.  THE FORCE APPLIED TO THE LOAD LOCKS WAS SUFFICIENTLY TO BREAK THEM.  THE SHRINK-WRAP BANDING ALSO FAILED AND SEVERAL DRUMS TURNED OVER.  ONE HALF FULL DRUM OF WASTE NITRIC ACID SLID INTO A "DRUM DOLLY" WITH THE PRONGS PUNCTURING THE TOP OF THE DRUM JUST BELOW THE MIDLINE ALLOWING APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS OF THE WASTE NITRIC ACID TO SPILL IN THE VAN. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY DAMMED THE REAR AREA OF THE VAN WITH SORBENT MATERIAL.  THE DAMAGED DRUM, ALL SPILLED MATERIAL AND SORBENT WAS PLACED INTO AN 85 GAL. OVRPACK.  THE VAN, DRUMS AND AREA WAS DECONTAMINATED.  THE LOAD WAS DELIVERED TO THE DISPOSAL SITE.

OUR UNIT ARRIVED AT THE INTERNATIONAL TECHNOLOGIES PLANT SITE AT 1330 PROCEEDED TO THE OFF LOADING SITE WHERE OUR DRIVER CONNECTED UP OUR HOSE TO THE TANK TRAILER AND OUR PRODUCT PUMP AND THEN WITH THE HELP OF CUSTOMER PERSONNEL, RAN A 100 FT OF DISCHARGE HOSE TO THE CUSTOMERS STORAGE TANK AND PUT END OF HOSE INTO TOP OF TANK.  THE OFF LOADING WAS OKAY UNTIL ONE OF THE HELPERS, WHO WAS ON TOP OF THE STORAGE TANK, SAID THE TANK WAS FULL SO THE PUMPING AND OFF LOADING WAS SHUT DOWN,  OUR UNIT WAS TO MOVE TO ANOTHER STORAGE TANK, BUT, FIRST THE PRODUCT IN THE 100 FT OF DISCHARGE HOSE HAD TO BE DRAINED OF PRODUCT.  CUSTOMER PERSONNEL THEN GOT A 55 GALLON DRUM AND FILLED IT, THEN GOT A SECOND DRUM, AND SPILLED APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS ON THE GROUND.  THE CUSTOMER STATED THAT THEY WOULD CLEAN UP TEH SPILLED PRODUCT.  SOME PRODUCT GOT ON TWO OF THE OPERATORS, AND THEY WENT TO THE SAFETY SHOWER AND WASHED OFF.

column168: OUR DRIVER, LOU GREGOIRE, UNLOADED HYDROCHLORIC ACID INTO THE WRONG STORAGE TANK WHICH CONTAINED SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE.  THE MIXTURE OF THE TWO (2) CHEMICALS RELEASED CHLORINE GAS INTO THE AIR.  LOU IMEDIATELY SHUT THE UNLOADING VALVE ON THE TANKER, BUT INHALED SOME CHLORINE GAS ALONG WITH THREE (3) OTHER PERSONS WHO WERE WORKING NEXT DOOR.  THEY WERE ALL TREATED AND RELEASED FROM THE LOCAL HOSPITAL.  THE TITUSVILLE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND BREVARD COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT.  THE ERROR WAS CONCLUDED TO BE BY THE DRIVER'S NEGLIGENCE; THEREFORE, HE WAS DISCIPLINED WITH A THREE (3) DAY SUSPENSION.

column168: JACKSON TRANSPSORT WENT TO GREAT WESTERN CHEM. CO. MILE 17.5 SPUR RD TO PICK-UP 8 DRUMS SULFURIC ACID.  ACCESS TO LOADING DOCK WAS UNAVAILABLE BECAUSE OF SNOW, ICE AND SLUSH SO DRUMS WERE TAIL LOADED WITH FORK LIFT ON PALLETS.  DRUMS WERE SHRUNK WRAPPED TOGETHER (4 PER PALLET) TO SECURE AND LOADED BY GREAT WESTERN AS DRIVER APPLIED PLACARDS AND CHECKED CONDITION OF TRUCK & TRAILER. JACKSON TRANSPORT THEN PROCEEDED TO ANCHORAGE WHERE DRIVER STOPPED AT MILE 38 OF SEWARD HWY TO TAKE A SHORT BREAK AND AGAIN CHECKING CONDITION.  NO LEAK WAS DETECTED AT THAT TIME, HOWEVER AFTER DRIVING THROUGH SLUSHY SNOW & RAIN, WATER WAS DRIPPING FROM THE TRUCK AND TRAILER IN LARGE AMOUNTS. DRIVER THEN PROCEEDED TO ANCHORAGE, WHEN HE STOPPED AT THE POTTER SCALE. THE LEAK WAS THEN DETECTED.  DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CALLED GREAT WESTERN IN ANCH. AND GREAT WESTERN SENT A CLEAN UP TEAM TO THE SITE.  THR ALASKA STATE TROOPER INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER NOT TO OPEN THE DOORS OF THE VAN UNTIL THE CLEAN-UP TEAM ARRIVED. WHEN THE CLEAN-UP TEAM ARRIVED, SODA ASH WAS PLACED AND ALL SPILL DRIP AREAS INSIDE THE VAN AND ON THE GROUND AND ON THE SCALE AREA.  THE ACID WAS THEREFORE NEUTRALIZED IMMEDIATELY AND NO DANGER EXISTED TO PERSON OR PROPERTY. AT SOME POINT THE STATE TROOPERS OR THE SALE OPERATOR CALLED FOR INDEPENDENT CLEAN-UP RESPONSE IN THE FORM OF ANCHORAGE FIRE DEPT., ANCH. POLICE DEPT., NORTHWEST ENVIRONMENTAL INC. AND SO FORTH.  THESE PEOPLE WERE NOT NEEDED AS THE ACID WAS ALREADY NEUTRALIZED.  GREAT WESTERN SENT ONE DRIVER BACK TO ANCHORAGE TO OBTAIN ADDITIONAL EQUIPMENT SUCH AS PUMPS, CONTAINERS, MASKS & SO FORTH.  THE CLEAN-UP OPERATIONS WERE WELL UNDER CONTROL WITHOUT ASSISTANCE FROM OUTSIDE ORGANIZATIONS WHEN THE STATE TROOPERS ORDERED GREAT WESTERN PEOPLE OUT OF AND AWAY FROM THE VAN. IN THE FACE OF ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE AND NEEDLESS PUBLICITY, 1 BELIEVED GREAT WESTERN'S PRIMARY CONCERN WAS TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACID AND THEN PROCEED WITH CLEAN-UP IN AN ORGANIZED MANNER, AT WHICH POINT THE SITUATION WAS TAKEN OUT OF THEIR HANDS, AND THEY WERE NOT ALLOWED TO PERFORM. FUTURE SHIPMENTS OF ACID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHOUDL BE PLACED IN THE FRONT OF THE VAN OR AGAINST A BULKHEAD SO AS TO RIDE MORE STABLE AGAINST THE POOR HIGHWAY CONDITIONS OF THE SEWARD AND STERLING HIGHWAYS DURING BREAK-UP MONTHS.

column168: WHILE OFFLOADING FERRIC CHLORIDE SOLUTION FROM ECOFF TRUCKING, INC.'S MC-311 CARGO TANK TRAILER INTO CONSUMER OF ILLINOIS'S HOLDING TANK, PRODUCT BEGAN TO LEAK FROM A 3-INCH TO 2-INCH FLANGE ADAPTER FITTING. THE LEAK OCCURRED DUE TO A ALUMINUM NIPPLE.  THE ECOFF DRIVER MISTAKENLY USED A 2-INCH ALUMINUM NIPPLE WHICH IS INCOMPATIBLE WITH FERRIC CHLORIDE SOLUTION. THE FERRIC CHLORIDE CORRODED THE 2-INCH ALUMINIUM NIPPLE, THUS CAUSING THE LEAK TO DEVELOP.  THE LEAK WAS IMMEDIATELY DISCOVERED BY THE ECOFF DRIVER, WHO WAS MONITORING THE OFFLOADING PROCEDURE.  THIS DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE FLOW OF PRODUCT EXITING THE CARGO TANK TRAILER. THE PRODUCT REMAINING IN THE HOSE LINE, HOWEVER, LEAKED FROM THE CONNECTION WHERE THE NIPPLE HAD CORRODED. THE AMOUNT OF SPILLED PRODUCT WAS ESTIMATED TO BE BETWEEN 15 TO 25 GALLONS.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN A DIKED AREA THAT ENCIRLED THE HOLDING TANK.  CONSUMER OF ILLINOIS SUPERVISED THE CLEAN-UP AND SUBSEQUENT DECONTAMINATION EFFORTS.  IN THE OPINION OF ECOFF TRUCKING, INC., THIS PARTICULAR INCIDENT CAOULD HAVE BEEN AVOIDED BY USING ONLY EQUIPMENT (EG; FITTINGS, NIPPLES ETC.) THAT IS COMPATIBLE WITH THE CORROSIVE NATURE OF FERRIC CHLORIDE. THE INVOLVED ECOFF DRIVER HAS BEEN COUNSELED AS TO WHAT TYPES OF FITTINGS, ECT. ARE INSTRUCTED ITS DRIVERS TO NEVER USE ALUMINUM FITTINGS WITH A CORROSIVE PRODUCT, ADDITIONAL TRAINING WILL BE PROVIDED TO THE WORK FORCE TO INSURE AGAINST FUTURE OCCURRENCES.

FORKLIFT OPERATOR LOADING TRAILER INADVERTLY BACKED OVER THREE (3) SMALL PACKAGES CONTAINING MATERIALS LISTED IN SECTION 12.  THESE PACKAGES CONTAINED TWO (1) LITER EACH OF THE SUBJECT MATERIALS. THE MATERIALS LEAKED ONTO THE FLOOR NEAR THE TRAILER.  THE FORKTRUCK OPERATOR IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE SUPERVISOR.  THE SUPERVISOR EVACUATED AND SECURED THE AREA.  CHEMTREC WAS CALLED AS WAS THE FIRE DEPARTMENT. USING RESPIRATORS FROM OUR EMERGENCY SPILL KIT THE SUPERVISOR AND ANOTHER EMPLOYEE PLACED THE DAMAGED CARTONS IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND COVERED THE GENERAL AREA WITH ABSORBENT MATERIALS.  ENSIGHT ENVIRONMENTAL SITE RESTORATION, TUCKER, GA. WAS EMPLOYED TO REMOVE THE RESIDUAL MATERIAL AND SCRUB THE AREA TO FREE IT OF CONTAMINATION.  EIGHT EMPLOYEES INDICATED THEY FELT NAUSEATED AND WERE TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL.  THEY WERE TREATED AND RELEASED WITH NO APPARENT LASTING EFFECT.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT DEPARTED WITH NO FURTHER ACTION.

column168: WENT TO WORK ON 4-25-91 GOT OFF AT APPROXIMATELY 2:00PM WENT HOME, ATE DINNER, TOOK SHOWER, TALKED WITH FAMILY & WENT TO BED AT APPROX. 6:30PM GOT UP AT APPROX 1:30AM ON 4-26-91 GOT READY FOR WORK, HAD 1 CUP OF COFFEE AND LEFT FOR WORK.  GOT TO WORK AT APPROX. 2:15AM, DID PRECHECK AND LOADED TRUCK FOR PAYSON.  I LEFT FOR PAYSON AT APPROX. 3:00AM.  STARTED FOR PAYSON, STOPPED AT FOUR PEAKS TO BUMP TIRES AND RELIEVE MYSELF THEN CONTINUED ON TO PAYSON.  GOT NEAR THE TOP OF SLATE CREEK, WAS TALKING TO SOMEONE ON RADIO FROM MINN. WHO NEEDED DIRECTIONS TO MESA.  SHIFTED THE TRUCK UP ONE (1) GEAR & HAD A HARD TIME GETTING IT IN GEAR AND WHEN I LOOKED BACK AROUND I SAW HEADLIGHTS COMING STRAIGHT AT ME.  I FELT THAT IF I STOPPED THE TRUCK THERE WAS A GOOD POSSIBILITY HE WOULD HIT ME SO I DECIDED TO GO AS FAR TO THE RIGHT AS POSSIBLE TO AVOID HIM.  AS I STEERED TO THE RIGHT I FELT THE RIGHT FRONT WHEEL DROP OFF THE HIGHWAY INTO THE SOFT SHOULDER.  WHEN I APPLIED THE BRAKES THE TRUCK STARTED TO LIST TO THE RIGHT SO I LET OFF THE BRAKES AND GOT BACK ON THE THROTTLE TO KEEP TRUCK UPRIGHT.  I HIT SOME DIPS OR BUMPS AND LOST CONTROL OF THE TRUCK AT THAT POINT.  THE NEXT THING I REMEMBER WAS BEING ON THE GROUND OUTSIDE THE TRUCK AND I HEARD SOMETHING RUNNING & GOT UP AND PULLED THE EVC VALVE BUT IT DID NOT STOP.  I DO REMEMBER TURNING LIGHTS OUT ON TRUCK.  SOMEONE STOPPED TO ASK ME IF I WAS OK AND HE TOLD ME I WAS BLEEDING AND REACHED UP INTO TRUCK TO GET A TOWEL FOR MY HEAD AND THEN TOOK A TOWEL OUT OF HIS PICK-UP FOR ME ALSO.  I WENT TO THE TRUCK TO GET MY JACKET AND THE MAN SAID HE WOULD GET IT SO HE GOT THE COAT AND WE GOT INTO HIS PICK-UP AND HE TOOK ME UP TO THE HOSPITAL.  ANOTHER MAN THAT HAD STOPPED SAID HE WOULD STAY WITH THE TRUCK UNTIL THE POLICE GOT THERE.  WENT TO HOSPITAL AND WAS TREATED FOR HEAD INJURY.  WHILE BEING TREATED D.P.S. OFFICER WAS QUESTIONING ME ABOUT THE ACCIDENT.  ART CAME TO PICK ME UP AT HOSPITAL AND DRIVE ME TO MY HOME.

column168: 5 DIFFERENT COMPOUNDS WERE FOUND LEAKING AND THEN DETERMINED NATURE OF THE MATERIAL.  LOAD CONSISTED OF 80 DRUMS LOADED IN A 4-4-4 STRAIGHT STACK LOADING PATTERN ON THE FLOOR.  NO BLOCKING WAS PROVIDED FOR THIS LAYER.  A 2ND LAYER OF 24 DRUMS, ALSO A 4-4-4 PATTERN HAD 1/2 INCH PLYWOOD LAYER WLL BRACED.  MOST OF THE DRUMS AT REAR & LOWER LAYER HAD LIQUID ON TOP HEADS. THE SMALL BUNGS HAVE A SPRING-BALL VENT VALVE.  THIS WAS THE SOURCE OF THE LIQUID ON TOP OF DRUMS.  ONE DRUM OF SYNPRON 1322 LOADED IN THE RIGHT FRONT CORNER WAS LEAKING DUE TO RUB THRU OF TOP ROLLING HOOP ACCOUNT CONTACT WITH ADJACENT DRUM.  THE RUB MARKS IN THE PAINT ON THIS FRAME RAIL INDICATED BOTH CORNER DRUMS WERE LOADED ON TOP OF THIS RAIL.  THIS TILTED THE DRUMS SLIGHTLY & CAUSED THE RIGHT DRUM TO RUB AGAINST THE ADJACENT DRUM WHICH RESUTED ON THE RUB THRU CONDITION.  DRUMS WERE WIPED CLEAN & CAREFULLY INSPECTED.  INTERIOR OF CONTAINER WAS CLEANED & DRUMS RELOADED. THE LEAKER WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WAS PLACED AT RIGHT REAR CORNER.  PRIOR TO OVERPACKING THE LEAKING DRUM, THE WORN AREA WAS TAPED.

column168: THE DRIVER HAD LOADED PRODUCT AT THE CHEVRON TERMINAL IN CHARLESTON, WVA. THE LOAD WAS A SPLIT DELIVERY BETWEEN WINFIELD, WVA AND SCOTT DEPOT, WVA. THE DRIVER HAD LOADED 2800 GALLONS UNLEADED GAS IN #1 COMPARTMENT, 1950 GALLONS UNLEADED GAS IN #2 COMPARTMENT, 1250 GALLONS DIESEL IN #3 COMPARTMENT AND 2500 GALLONS UNLEADED GAS IN #4 COMPARTMENT.  THE DRIVER WAS TO UNLOAD COMPARTMENTS #1 AND #3 AT THE WINFIELD LOCATION.  THE DRIVER MADE AN ERROR IN THINKING THIS STATION WAS TO RECEIVE 4450 GALLONS OF NOLEAD.  DRIVER NOTICED THAT THE CAP HAD BLOWN OFF AND GASOLINE WAS COMING OUT AROUND DROP FITTING.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN AND ALERTED THE STATION ATTENDANT.  THE TEAYS VALLEY VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED. THEY WERE ABLE TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL OF PRODUCT WITH ABSORBENT MATERIALS. THE DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES ALSO INVESTIGATED THE SPILL.  THE DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES CLEARED THE AREA OF ANY CLEANUP.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0900 ON APRIL 9, 1991, CREWMAN OPERATING TRAIN Q-HOBA1-08 DETECTED A  LEAK FROM THE DOME COVER ON RAIL TANK CAR UTLX 972.  MATERIAL WAS ESCAPING INTO THE AIR AT A SLOW RATE.  THIS LOAD WAS SET OUT OF THE TRAIN AND LEFT AT TEJON, NM, A SIDING ABOUT FOUR MILES WEST OF VAUGHN, NM. THIS AREA IS ISOLATED RANGE LAND.  TWO MECHANICAL SUPERVISORS FROM BELEN, NM WERE AT ONCE DISPATCHED TO MAKE REPAIRS.  THEIR CLOSE INSPECTION REVEALED PROBLEMS IN THE TOP UNLOADING ASSEMBLY OF COMPARTMENT NO. 1. THREE OF FOUR BOLTS WERE FOUND TO BE LOOSE, AND ONE NUT MISSING ON THE AIR CONNECTION BLIND FLANGE.  ALSO, A VALVE WAS FOUND IN THE OPEN POSITION WITH ITS HANDLE MISSING.  AFTER MAKING APPROPRIATE REPAIRS, THE LOAD WAS RELEASED BY MECHANICAL PERSONNEL AT 1045 HOURS ON APRIL 9, 1991.

TWO DRUMS WERE LEAKING FROM PIN HOLES AT EITHER END OF A LARGE DENT.  CLEAN-UP WAS COMPLETED AND LOAD PROCEEDED ON WITHOUT FURTHER PROBLEMS.  PEOPLE CONTACTED WERE STATE OF KENTUCKY DISASTER EMERGENCY SERVICES, WALTON, KY POLICE, BOONE COUNTY SHERIFF, WALTON FIRE DEPT., BOONE COUNTY DISASTER AND EMERGENCY SERVICES AND FEDERAL EPA AT ATLANTA, GA.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: VEHICLE #1 (OUR COMPANY UNIT) WAS WEST BOUND ON HWY 82 WHEN VEHICLE #2 EAST BOUND ON HWY 82 CROSSED OVER THE CENTER LINE, STRIKING VEHICLE #1. THE DRIVER'S SIDE FRONT QUARTER OF VEHICLE #2 STRUCK THE DRIVER'S SIDE FRONT QUARTER OF VEHICLE #1.  AFTER IMPACT, VEHICLE #1 LEFT THE HIGHWAY ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE ROAD AND OVERTURNED.  ONE COMPARTMENT DOME LID CAME OPEN CAUSING SPILLAGE OF #2 FUEL OIL.  SPILLAGE WAS REPORTED TO THE DOT AND NRC.  IT WAS REPORTED TO ADEM BY THE LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM.

THE ABOVE SHIPMENT CAME TO TAMPA ON TRIALER ORL 8662 IN POSITION 25 ON THE STACKING REPORT.  THE WRITE UP STATED THAT POSITION 27, PRO 51038556, WAS BETWEEN THE WALL OF THE TRIALER AND THE PALET OF MONITOR 4 SPRAY.  WHEN THE PALET WAS UNLOADED FROM THE INBOUND TRIALER THE BUNDLE OF RODS CAME SLIDING DOWN PUNTURING A HOLE IN THE BOTTOM PAIL OF THE PALET.  THE DOCKMAN TORN THE SHRINK WRAP AND TURNED THE 5-GAL PAIL OVER TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE AND WRAPPED THE PAIL IN 2 TRASH BAGS SECURING THE BAGS WITH TAPE.  THE DOCKMAN AND SUPERVISOR SPRAYED THE DOCK, AND THE PALETS OFF THE WATER AND PUT THE WRAPPED PAIL IN THE HAZ.  MATERIAL AREA OF THE WAREHOUSE.  THIS HAPPENED BETWEEN 02:00 AND 02:30.  I ARRIVED TO WORK AT 07:15 AND WAS TOLD BY OPERATIONS TO CALL CHEMTREC AND REPORT THE SPILL.  I DID.  A SPOKE TO MR. MILLAZZO AND WAS TOLD THAT HE COULD CONTACT THE SHIPPER AND THEY, THE SHIPPER WOULD BE IN TOUCH WITH ME.  AT 13:00 HRS I CALLED ORL FOR THE SHIPPERS PHONE NUMBER FOR ASSISTANCE. A THEN SPOKE TO DAVID NOLES AND WAS TOLD A TERRY WOULD BE IN CONTACT WITH ME WITH DISPO. I HAVE NOT RECEIVED DISPO TO DATE.  I ALSO SPOKE TO DAVE WITH AACT SAFETY AND I WAS TOLD HOW TO DISPOSE OF THE HAZ. I SUITED UP IN THE HAZARDOUS SUIT WITH GLOVES AND MASK AND PUT THE 5 GAL PAIL IN A 60 GAL DRUM.  PUT OIL SOAK MATERIAL ON THE GROUND TO PREVENT DAMAGE TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  I THEN SHOVELED THE MATERIAL AND PUT THAT MERCHANDISE IN THE DRUM WITH THE PAIL. THE QUANTITY THAT LEAKED WAS MINOR.  THE FUMES WERE NOT.  AFTER I CLEANED THE YARD AND DOCK OF THE HAZARD I HAD A DOCKMAN PUT THE DRUM IN A SAFE MANOR IN AN OUT OF THE WAY AREA TO PREVENT ANOTHER ACCIDENT FROM HAPPENING.  THE SALVAGE DRUM WAS SEALED AND THE HAZARDOUS SUIT, RUBBER GLOVES, AND MASK WERE PUT IN A TRASH BAG AND ALSO PUT IN A SAFE PLACE.  TO PREVENT THIS SORT OF INCIDENT FROM HAPPENING AGAIN IN THE FUTURE I SUGGEST PLACING HAZARDOUS CARGO AWAY FROM ANY SHARP OBJECTS OR HAVE DUNAGE AROUND THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TO PREVENT PUNCTURE OR LEAKAGE.  AACT HAVE STRICT GUIDE LINES FOR WHEN THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT HAPPENS.  I DO NOT BELIEVE THESE WERE MET.  THE SPILL KIT WAS FORWARDED TO MOBAY CORP, 8400 HAWTHORN AVE,  KANSAS CITY MO FOR RECLAIMING AND CREDIT CLM #3373-91 FOR $257.70. THE DRUM LEFT TAMPA ON 05-14-91 ON PRO 52024521 AT 100 LBS.  DRUM WAS LABELED WITH ALL APPROPRIATE LABELS.     TIM PHILLIPS TAM I/B OSD.

ON APRIL 10, 1991, AT APPROXIMATELY 2:30 PM. RANDY RETHLAKE WAS TRAVELING WEST ON MAIN STREET/HWY 59 IN MARSHALL MINNESOTA.  AS RANDY APPROACED THE STOP LIGHT HE WAS FORCED TO BREAK QUICJKYU CAUSING (1) ONE OF THE 4 MINI BULK TANKS TO OVERTURN INSIDE THE TRUCK.  THE TANK CRACKED AND PRODUCT BEGAN LEAKING OUT.  RANDY PULLED OF THE ROAD INTO A PARKING AREA AND CALLED FOR HELP OTHER AT THE SEEN PROVIDED ASSISTANCE.  OUR COMPANY, TRI LINE CO-OP DISPATCHED OUR SAFETY DIRECTOR AND A CLEAN UP CREW WITH CONTAINMENT MATERIALS.  WHEN THE TRI LINE CREW ARRIVED, ACTION HAD TAKEN PLACED TO COLLECT LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TRUCK.  OUR MEN THEN BEGAN SPREADING ABSORBENT MATERIAL IN THE TRUCK TO HELP PREVENT THE LEAKING OF ANY MORE PRODUCT.  WHEN IT WAS ASSURED THAT PRODUCT WAS NO LONGER LEAKING FROM THE TRUCK, ALL MATERIALS WERE HAULED BACK TO OUT PLANT.  IN FUTURE, TRANSPORTING MINI BULK CONTAINERS ARE INSPECTED THOUROUGLLY, AND LOADED IN A MANNER THAT WOULD HELP PREVENT ANY OVERTURNING. ALL TIE DOWNS ARE CHECKED FOR DAMAGE TO INSURE PROPER STRENGTH.

column168: LOADED MATERIAL ON TRUCK AND APPLIED SHRINK WRAP TO PALLET.  PUT PALLET IN CENTER FRONT OF TRUCK BED WIHT NO SIDE BOARDS AND FAILED TO REMEMBER TO TIE DOWN.  DROVE 7 MILES SOUTH FROM MONROE, OREGON TO LINGO LANE.  DROVE 1/2 MILE DOWN LINGO LANE AND TOOK A CORNER TOO FAST CAUSING PALLET TO SLIDE OFF OF THE LEFT SIDE OF TRUCK BED ON A RIGHT TURN GOING EAST ON SAID LANE. CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP WITH LIME, BLEACH, AND FLOOR DRY UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF THE LANE COUNTY POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENTS.  APPROXIMATELY 8 TO 10 GALLONS OF VELPAR L RECOVERED IN FLOOR DRY, DIRT, AND GRAVEL. APPROXIMATLEY 3 GALLONS WERE ABSORBED IN LIME WITH BLEACH.  ALL SOLIDS WERE TAKEN TO MONROE TREE FARMS AND SPREAD WITH A FERTILIZER SPREADER AT RATES ALREADY IN ACCORDANCE WITH LABEL STANDARDS.  ACCIDENT REPORTED IMMEDIATELY TO DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY AND THE OREGON DEPARTMENT OF MOTOR VEHICLES.  WE WERE NOT AWARE AT THIS TIME THAT REPORTING TO THE DEPARTMENT OF MOTOR VEHICLES WAS ALSO BECESSARY, THUS THE TARDINESS OF THIS REPORT.

column168: DRIVER ARRIVED AT CONSIGNEE WITH TRACTOR-CARGO LOADED WITH GASOLINE FOR DELIVERY INTO UST.  DRIVER LEFT GATE VALVE (EXTERNAL VALVE) PARTIALLY OPEN FROM HIS PRIOR DELIVERY.  WHEN HE REMOVED THE DUCT CAP FROM DISCHARGE OUTLET TO ATTACHED HOSE, PRODUCT FLOWED FROM THE WET-LINE OF TRAILER - INTERNAL (EMERGENCY VALVE WAS CLOSED) LIMITING PRODUCT LOSS TO PRODUCT IN WET-LINE.  SPILL OCCURRED AT THIS POINT.  FIRE DEPT. CALLED THE SCENE. REPORT MADE TO FLORIDA DEPARTMENT REGULATION.  DRIVER WAS SPLASHED WITH GASOLINE.  GASOLINE BEGAN TO IRRITATE DRIVER'S SKIN; HE PROCEEDED TO RINSE HIMSELF OFF WITH GARDEN HOSE, SOME WATER ALSO APPLIED TO AREA OF GASOLINE SPILL.  FIRE DEPT. PUT OIL DRY ON AREA OF GAS SPILL SOAKING UP RESIDUE. THIS MATERIAL WAS THEN SWEPT UP AND PUT INTO A PLASTIC LINED 554 GALLON DRUM, WHICH WAS LABELED WITH A UN 1203 PLACARD AND RETURNED TO FLEET TRANSPORT PROPERTY FOR LATER DISPOSAL.  ALL DRIVERS HAVE BEEN REMINDED THROUGH WRITTEN NOTIFICATION TO BE SURE TO CHECK ALL VALVES TO BE THEY ARE TIGHTLY CLOSED BEFORE REMOVING LUST CAPS FROM DISCHARGE LINES ON CARGO TANKS.  THIS WILL BE COVERED AGAIN AT OUR NEXT SAFETY MEETING, WITHIN THE NEXT MONTH.

column168: ON THE NIGHT OF 04-05-91, I, KAREN NICHOLAS/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORD. OF ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH 45177, DISCOVERED A SHPT LEAKING A CLEAR LIQUID.  THE LOCATION OF THE LEAKING SHPT WAS INSIDE DOOR C-45 OF OUR SORT FACILITY.  THE SHIPMENT WAS IN A FIBERBOARD BOX THAT HAD NO HAZARD MARKINGS OR LABELS, NOR DID IT HAVE ANY HAZARD CERTIFICATION ATTACHED TO IT.  UPON OPENING THE FIBERBOARD BOX I FOUND THREE TWO OUNCE PLASTIC BOTTLES WITH PLASTIC SCREW-TYPE CLOSURE LIDS.  APPROXIMATELY 1 TO 1.5 OUNCES HAD LEAKED OUT OF EACH OF THE PLASTIC BOTTLES.  NON OF THE 3 BOTTLES WERE DAMAGED IN ANY WAY.  THE LEAK APPEARED TO BE A RESULT OF LOOSE LIDS THAT HAD NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THEM CLOSED.  ACCORDING TO A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET PROVIDED INSIDE THE BOX,  THE LIQUID IS METHYL ETHYL KETONE PEROXIDE, ORGANIC PEROXIDES, N.O.S., UN2550.  ALSO LOADED INSIDE THE SAME FIBERBOARD BOX I FOUND THREE 1-GALLON CANS THAT WERE ALL INTACT.  ACCORDING TO THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET PROVIDED, THESES CANS CONTAINED POLYESTER RESIN TYPE V, RESIN SOLUTION, FLAMMABLE LIQUID, UN 1866.  THERE WERE NO HAZARD MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THESE CANS.  THE CANS WERE METAL, 1 GALLON CAPACITY WITH FRICTION TYPE LIDS.  THE LIDS WERE SECURED WITH CLIPS.  THE ONLY MATERIAL USED WAS CRUMPLED PAPER.  THIS SHIPMENT IS CURRENTLY BEING HELD IN OUR HAZ-MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY.  IT WILL BE TRACKED TO ITS DESTINATION UPON RELEASE BY THE FAA IN A D.O.T. APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM AFTER IT HAS BEEN BROKEN DOWN INTO2 SEPARATE LEGAL SHIPMENTS.

column168: PASSENGER MRS.  LUGARDO CARRIED A STRAW TYPE SHOPPING BAG ON BOARD THE AIRCRAFT AND PLACED THE BAG IN THE OVERHEAD STORAGE BIN DIRECTLY ABOVE ROW 17D,E,F.  FOLLOWING A ROUTINE DEPARTURE FROM DFW SOME PASSENGERS COMPLAINED OF AN ODOR OF FUEL IN THE CABIN.  THE FLIGHT CREW ELECTED TO DIVERT TO SAT AS A PRECAUTION.  UPON INVESTIGATION THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR WAS FOUND TO BE EMINATING FOR MS.  LUGARDO'S CARRY ON BAG.  CONTENTS OF THE BAG WERE: 2 CANS OF "GUNK" ENGINE CLEANER, 1 CAN STP OIL TREATMENT, 1 PLASTIC SPRAY BOTTLE OF "ARMOR ALL:, 8 PLASTIC BOTTLES OF STP CARBURETOR CLEANER.  ALL OF THESE ITEMS WERE REMOVED FROM THE AIRCRAFT.  THE OVERHEAD BIN WAS CLEANED AND THE FLIGHT DEPARTED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER 15-4836 AT OUR SPENCER, IA DOCK, ONE PLASTIC DRUM WAS PUNCTURED AT THE BOTTOM, WHEN A FORKLIFT PUSHED A WOODEN PALLET INTO THE DRUM.  A VERY SMALL STREAM OF THE PRODUCT STARTING LEAKING OUT OF THE DRUM.  AFTER CHECKING OUR EMERGENCY REPONSE GUIDE IT WAS DETERMINED THAT IT WAS SAFE TO PROCEED.  WE TURNED THE DRUM ONTO ITS SIDE TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER SPILLAGE.  WE CONTACTED THE EMERGENCY NUMBER ON THE BILL OF LADING, AND RECEIVED A RETURN CALL FROM MR RALPH SIMPSON OD DUBOIS CO, THE SHIPPER.  HE FAXED US COPIES MSDS SHEETS ON THIS PRODUCT AN ADVISED US ON CLEAN UP PROCEDURES.  THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON SPILLED ON THE FLOOR OF OUR TRAILER.  WE APPLIED FLOOR DRY TO TAKE UP THE LIQUID AND PUT IN A 5 GALLON PLASTIC BUCKET.  MR SIMPSON ALSO AUTHORIZED THE RETURN OF THE DAMAGED DRUM,  IT WAS PUT IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER. NO OTHER FREIGHT WAS CONTAMINATED.  WE HAVE APPROXIMATELY 2 LBS OF MATERIAL USED TO CLEAN UP SPILL, WITH DISPOSAL PENDING.

column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL (SSA/HM) TOM SMITH WAS CONTACTED BY UNION PACIFIC EMPLOYEES AT PORT LAREDO, TX THAT VTRZ 236106 HAD PRODUCT LEAKING.  SSA/HM SMITH CALLED INTEROX AMERICA (CHEMICAL MAKER) AND SPOKE WITH KENNETH REED, EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM CAPTAIN.  SSA/HM SMITH AND CAPTAIN REED MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO MEET IN LAREDO, TX TO RESTACK AND REBLOCK THE TOP ROW OF DRUMS THAT HAD BEEN IMPROPERLY LOADED. TANK CAR WAS NOT ACTIVELY LEAKING AND IT HAD BEEN ISOLATED UNTIL INSPECTION/REPAIR. SSA/HM ROBINSON'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE RUPTURE DISC HAD FAILED. SSA/HM ROBINSON CONTACTED CHEMTREC (JIM COOPER), GEORGIA GULF (STEVE VARNADO), LOUISIANA STATE POLICE AND LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY.

MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS R. A THULL NOTIFIED SHIPPER VULCAN CHEMICAL IN REGARDS TO LEAKING TANK CAR. VULCAN CHEMICAL REPRESENTATIVE JOE HOSSE DISPATCHED  A TRUCK DRIVER FROM THEIR TERMINAL IN MCALESTER, OKLAHOMA TO RESPOND TO VAN BUREN TO REPLACE 1235 POUND RUPTURE DISC. MANAGER, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE, R.M. STINE WAS NOTIFIED BY WICHITA, KS YARDMASTER (RON BUDIMLIJA) ADVISING TANK CAR IMCX 2057 WAS LEAKING. MANAGER STINE'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT CAR HAD A SLIGHT LIQUID LEAK FROM THE BASE OF THE "B" END LIQUID VALVE.  CAUSE WAS THE TWO NUTS ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE VALVE WERE SLIGHTLY LOOSE.  AFTER SECURING THE NUTS A CHECK WAS MADE WITH "SNOOP" AND NO FURTHER EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE WAS NOTED. (PRODUCT WAS VAPORIZING IMMEDIATELY UPON RELEASE AS WEATHER CONDITIONS WERE CLOUDY, SE WING 20 MPH AND 62 DEGREES F). CHEMTREC (SUSAN TRACY/#6476), KANSAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENT (LARRY KNOCHE) AND IMC CHEMICALS (ROBERT MOLITOR) WERE ALL NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT.

column168: MANAGER, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS EMERGENCY RESPONSE, R.M. STINE, NOTED TANK CAR GATX 65253 HAD EVIDENCE OF PRODUCT HAVING SPLASHED FROM SAFETY VENT. MANAGER STINE'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE OSECO 100 LB TEST FRANGIBLE DISC HAD BURST.  ALSO, THE SAFETY VENT HOUSING FLANGE WAS IN A VERY DETERIORATED CONDITION (CRACKS IN THREE LOCATIONS AND WARPED).  AFTER REMOVING THE SAFETY CHAIN FROM THE DETERIORATED FLANGE, MANAGER STINE REPLACED WITH A NEW FLANGE (GATX 261-44), HE ALSO REPLACED THE FRANGIBLE DISC WITH A NEW "OSECO" DISC AND SECURED FITTINGS. MANAGER STINE ALSO NOTED EVIDENCE OF A SLIGHT LEAK FROM THE MANWAY NOZZLE WHICH UPON HIS INSPECTION, FOUND THAT SIX OF THE EIGHT MANWAY SWING EYE BOLTS WERE LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT.  THESE NUTS WERE TIGHTENED AND CAR WAS RELEASED FOR CONTINUED TRANSPORTATION.  CHEMTREC (TOM FLORES/RPT #6483) WAS NOTIFIED.

CAR WAS ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. SSA/HM COOPER'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE RUPTURE DISC HAD BURST ON THE SAFETY VENT LOCATED ON TOP OF THE MANWAY COVER. NO OTHER EXCEPTIONS WERE NOTED AND CAR WAS RELEASED TO THE CONSIGNEE.

column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) DEAN WHITELEY, WHILE MAKING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS AT ALBINA YARD, PORTLAND, OREGON, NOTED A SMALL LEAK AROUND THE THREE COMPARTMENT TANK CAR UTLX 2601. SSA/HM WHITELEY REMOVED THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP AND OBSERVED A LEAK AT A RATE OF ONE DRIP PER FIVE SECONDS FROM TEH INTERNALT BOTOM OUTLET VALVE. TO THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS REPLACED WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK FROM AROUND THE THREADS. CHEMTREC (SUSIE TRACY), SHIPPER (BILL PTACK), CONSIGNEE (KEVIN HUTCHENSON) WERE CONTACTED.

ON THE NIGHT ON 4-17-91 I RANDY WILLIAMS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPECIALIST OF ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DR., WILMINGTON, OH 45177 DISCOVERED A SHIPMENT LEAKING A CLEAR LIQUID FROM AN EXPRESS ENVELOPE.  THE LOCATION OF THE LEAKING SHPT WAS AT "C" BLDG., SECONDARY 4, TABLE 7.  UPON OPENING THE EXPRESS ENVELOPE I FOUND ONE 4 OZ. GLASS BOTTLE WITH A PLASTIC SCREW-TYPE CLOSURE UNSECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS.  APPROXIMATELY 2 OZ. HAD LEAKED OUT OF THE GLASS BOTTLE.  THE BOTTLE WAS IN A FIBREBOARD BOX INSIDE THE EXPRESS ENVELOPE.  THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO THE BOTTLE, THE LEAK WAS DUE TO A LOOSE CLOSURE. THERE WERE NO OTHER SIDE MARKINGS OR LABELS.  INNER BOX WAS MARKED "FLAMMABLE".  THIS SHIPMENT IS CURRENTLY BEING HELD IN OUR HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY.  IT WILL BE TRUCKED TO DESTINATION UPON RELEASE BY THE FAA., IN A D.O.T. APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM.

REPAIRS MADE: (1) TIGHTENED TOP-OPERATING HANDLE 1/2 TURN TO CLOSE BOTTOM VALVE. (2) REPLACED TOP_OPERATING ROD PACKING GLAND.  (3)TIGHTENED BELLY CAP.  REPAIRED TANKCAR BY 1950 ET.

ON 4/23/91, AT 7:00 P.M., KYLE BREAUX WAS ATTEMPTING TO PICK UP A PALLET OF PRODUCT TO BE LOADED.  WHILE LIFTING THE PALLET, ONE CASE OF METHYL ALCOHOL FELL, HITTING THE CONCRETE FLOOR.  ONE PINT OF THE METHYL ALCOHOL BROKE, SOAKING THE FIBERBORAD BOX.  THE AREA WAS ISOLATED AND THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP.  THE LOADERS WERE ADVISED TO CHECK PALLETS TO SEE THAT THE PRODUCT IS SECURE BEFORE MOVING THE PALLETS.

APPX 0800 HRS 4/17/91 K. KENKLE OPENED THE TRAILER UP TO FIND A LIQUID ON THE FLOOR.  WHEN I INVESTIGATED I FOUND THE LIQUID TO BE A CORROSIVE LIQUID COMING OUT OF THE TOP OF A TOTE TANK ON THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. THE LID ON THE TOTE TANK HAD A HOLE IN IT AND THE LIQUID WAS SPLASHING OUT OF IT AS THE TRAILER MOVED DOWN THE HIGHWAY.  I CONTACTED RALPH SIMPSON AT DUBOIS CHEMICAL IN SHARONVILLE, OHIO AND EXPLAINED PROBLEM.  HE SAID THEY HAD THE WRONG LID ON IT AND FOR US TO HOLD IT HERE ON OUR DOCK AND THEY WOULD SEND A REPLACEMENT LID 4/18/91.  TRAILER WAS CLEANED IN MANNER MR. SIMPSON ADVISED BY D. SMITH AND TOM MCGARVEY.  THE CORROSIVE LIQUID GOT ONTO SOME OTHER PACKAGES ALSO FROM DUBOIS AND MR. SIMPSON REQUESTED WE SHIP THEM BACK TO THEM.

column168: ON APRIL 19, 1991, 1 REPORTED A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INCIDENT BY TELEPHONE TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.  THE REPORT WAS LOGGED IN AS REPORT NUMBER 68719. THIS WAS DONE IN ORDER TO COMPLY WITH 49CFR171.15(A) (2). AT THE TIME, WE DID NOT KNOW WHETHER THE INJURED PARTY WOULD REQUIRE HOSPITALIZATION.  AS IT TURNED OUT, HE WAS TREATED AT THE HOSPITAL SENT HOME.  MS.  DIANE LAVALLE OF THE DOT HAS GIVEN HAS GIVEN ME A DEFINITION OF "HOSPITALIZATION" AS IT APPLIES TO THIS TO THIS REGUALTION.  FOR A PERSON TO BE HOSPITALIZATION, HE MUST BE "CHECKED IN" AND "ASSIGNED A BED".  THIS INCIDENT DID NOT MEET THIS CRITERIA AND, IN RETROSPECT, IT WAS NOT NECESSARY TO MAKE THE REPORT.  I INTERPRET 49CFR171.16 TO REQUIRE THAT A WRITTEN REPORT BE SUBMITTED ON FORM F-5800-1 IF A VERBAL REPORT HAS BEEN SUBMITTED.  THIS FORM IN DUPLICATE IS ENCLOSED.  A DESCRIPTION OF THE INCIDENT FOLLOWS:  OUR PLANT OPERATOR, MR. JIM SELBY, WAS LOADING A TWO COMPARTMENT TANK TRAILER.  THE TRAILER DID NOT BELONG TO OUR COMPANY AND DID NOT HAVE A VENT VALVE TO CHECK FOR PRESSURE AT THE HOSE CONNECTION. AFTER FILLING ONE COMPARTMENT, HE WAS DISCONNECTING THE HOSE, PREPARING TO CONNECT TO THE SECOND COMPARTMENT TANK VALVE WAS NOT COMPLETELY CLOSED AND AS HE DISCONNECTED THE HOSE, MATERIAL WAS RELEASED AND HE WAS SPLASHED OVER THE FRONT OF HIS BODY. HE SHUT OFF THE VALE, WENT IMMEDIATLEY INTO THE SHOWER AND WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL WHERE HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED.  ACTION HAS BEEN TAKEN TO PREVENT A RE-OCCURENCE BY INSTALLING A VENT VALVE IN THE LOADING HOSE TO BE USED IN THOSE INSTANCES WHERE THE TANK TRAILER BEING LOADED DOES NOT HAVE ONE.  IF THERE ARE ANY QUESTIONS CONCERNING THIS INCIDENT, PLEASE CONTACT ME.

DELIVERY DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY TO JM COMPUTERS SOUTHINGTON, CT. - A SHIPMENT OUT OF MACDERMID WATERBURY, CT GOING TO METAL FIN FORESTVILLE CT. WAS NEAR TAIL OF TRAILER - 3 DRUMS WERE ON 1 SKID & APPARENTLY ON ROAD 1 DRUM ROLLED OUT (AS DELIVERY WAS ON INCLINE) IT FELL TO GROUND HITTING DRIVERS HAD TRUCK AND PUTTING A SMALL PUNCTURE IN CTR. OF DRUM.  BOTH DRIVER & WITNESS (JOE ALFANO) SAID VERY MINIMAL QUANTITY LOST, MAYBE A QUART.  MACDERNID SENT OVER ONE OF THEIR PEOPLE WITH A RECOVERY DRUM & DUE TO WGHT.  APA CALLED MARVIN BROS, WHO HAVE A LIFTGATE UNIT TO PICK UP OVERPACK WITH DAMAGED DRUM - MARVIN BROS.  BROUGHT DRUM BACK TO MACDERMID THEMSELVES.  THIS COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED IF DRUMS WERE BANDED ON SKID.

column168: PACKAGE HAD STRONG ODOR; FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED 2 GLASS JSRS, BOTH BROKEN, WHICH APPARENTLY CONTAINED PAINT.  THE PACKAGE WAS NOT MARKED, LABELED, OR CERTIFIED AS CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THE LOCAL FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINSTRATION WAS NOTIFIED; SPECIAL AGENT BECKY ROHRING CONDUCTED THE INVESTIGATION.  THE PACKAGE WAS LATER RELEASED FOR DISPOSAL.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1300 HOURS, TUESDAY, APRIL 16, 1991, AAR/BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES INSPECTOR ALLEN RICHTER WAS SPLASHED BY PRODUCT FROM TANK CAR ECUX-37068 AT THE CONRAIL BAYONNE, NJ RAIL YARD.  MR. RICHTER, AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT, WAS PERFORMING ROUTINE INSPECTIONS OF TANK CARS AT THE RAIL YARD.  INSPECTING CAR CEUX-37068, MR. RICHTER FOUND THAT THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER OPENED WITH DIFFICULTY; AND AND ONCE OPEN, FOUND THAT THE HANDLE TO THE LIQUID UNLOADING LINE APPEARED IN A PARTIALLY OPEN POSITION.  IN PROCEEDING TO CORRECT THE  EXCEPTION, MR RICHTER OPENED THE AIR LINE AND NOTICED A HIGHER LEVEL OF PRESSURE THAN NORMAL FOR A RESIDUE GENERAL SERVICE TANK CAR.  THE LIQUID LINE PLUG WAS LOSSENED BUT DUE TO PRESSURE IN CAR CAME LOOSE.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT SPRAYED FROM THE OPEN LIQUID LINE ONTO MR. RICHTER. MR. RICHTER SECURED THAT AIR AND LIQUID LINES AND PROCEEDED TO THE CONRAIL YARD OFFICE WHERE HE WASHED OFF THE PRODUCT.  THERE WAS NO INJURY SUSTAINED BY MR. RICHTER AS S RESULT OF BEING SPLASHED BY THE PRODUCT.  EXXON CHEMICAL WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE LOCATION OF THE CAR.  CAR WAS REINSPECTED IN CONJUNCTION WITH DISTRICT INSPECTOR RICHTER AND SECURED.  CAR CLEARED TO DESTINATION AT 1600 HOURS, 04/16/91.

column25: DU PONT E I DE NEMOURS & CO
column168: ACTION PLAN: TO FORWARD A COPY OF THEIS REPORT TO DU PONT.  HAD THIS BEEN A LIFE-THREATENING EMERGENCY, WE HAD NO HELP FROM CHEMTREC.  VERY LITTLE INFORMATION PROVIDED BY DU PONT.  I HAVE SET UP A FOLDER WITH COPIES OF EVERY HAZARDOUS LOAD FOR THE VESSEL THAT IS AVAILABLE AT ANY HOUR TO ANYONE. DESCRIPTION OF EVENTS LOCATION: BARBOURS CUT #3, LA PORTE, TEXAS VESSEL: SEA-LAND ATLANTIC - AC033E DATE OF INCIDENT: 4/9/91 TIME: APPROXIMATELY 2145 HOURS CONTAINER #TEHU 823480 20'DV SEAL #PAKTANK 0100958 LOADED WITH DRUMS SAID TO CONTAIN 4 VINYL1CYCLOHEXENE, IMCO 3.2 DOT A UN1993 FLAMMABLE LIQUID, NOS. A. CONTAINER WAS LOADED ABOVE DECK ON VESSEL WHEN IT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING A SUBSTANCE PRODUCING NOXIOUS FUMES.  CONTAINER WAS IMMEDIATELY OFFLOADED AND MOVED TO SECURE AREA AWAY FROM SHIP AND PERSONNEL AT END OF DOCK ALONG STRINGPIECE. B. CALLED CHEMTREC WHO COULD NOT SUPPLY MSDS OR ANY OTHER HAZARDOUS INFORMATION REGARDING THIS CHEMICAL.  CHEMTREC CALLED DU PONT DIRECT. MR. FRANK NILAN OF DU PONT CALLED REQUESTING MORE INFORMATION CONCERNING INCIDENT AAND SAID HE WOULD HAVE SOMEONE LOCALLY CALL.  MR. STEVE BUCSANY, WITH DU PONT LA PORTE PLANT, CALLED BUT HE TOO DID NOT HAVE ANY INFORMATION ABOUT THIS CHEMICAL.  THEN SPOKE WITH MR. TED MILLER WITH DU PONT SABINE PLANT, AND HE TOO DID NOT HAVE ANY INFORMATION ON THIS CHEMICAL. C. THE PORT OF HOUSTON HAZARDOUS TEAM BROKE THE SEAL AND VERIFIED LABELS ON DRUMS. DRUMS SHOWED DU PONT PAPERS INSIDE CONTAINED INDICATED PAK TANK.  MARINE PERSONNEL CONTACTED PAK TANK IN GALENA PARK.  PAK TANK SENT OVER A HAZARDOUS TEAM.  PAK TANK SECURED THE LEAKING DRUMS, RE-BLOCKED AND BRACED THE LOAD.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: AT 2:05, IN THE MAIN SORT FACILITY, THERE WAS A PACKAGE LEAKING.  UPON INVESTIGATION OF THIS FIBREBOARD BOX, IT AS FOUND TO CONTAIN 3 - ONE QUART PLASTIC BOTTLES WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURES.  THE THREE PLASTIC BOTTLES CONTAINED "MEC" AND THE OTHER ONE CONTAINED ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL.  THE BOTTLE OF ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL WAS LEAKING INSIDE THE BOX, WHICH DID NOT CONTAIN ANY COMPATIBLE ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THERE WERE SEVERAL HUNDRED HEARING AIDS AND SOME TEST EQUIPMENT.  THERE WAS ALSO A SYRINGE AND A SMALL PLASTIC BOTTLE WITH THE NEEDLES EXPOSED ON THE END.  THE "MEC" WAS FOUND TO BE METHYL METHACRYLATE WHICH, ALONG WITH THE ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL, ARE REGULATED MATERIALS.  THE OUTER PKG. DID NOT HAVE  ANY MARKINGS, LABELS OR PROPER DOCUMENTATION THAT LED ME TO BELIEVE THAT THIS WAS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPPER SUPPLIED A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET THAT STATED THE MATERIALS ARE REGULATED FOR AIR TRANSPORT.

AT 0143 A FOAM MATERIAL WAS REPORTED ON THE SLIDE IN THE EXPRESS PACK AREA OF THE MAIN SORT.  UPON ARRIVAL ON SCENE 1, TONY FRYE, FOUND AN EXPRESS PACK THAT CONTAINED ONE AEROSOL CAN OF TEENAGE MUTANT TURTLE SOAP.  THIS WAS IN AN EXPRESS ENVELOPE THAT IS MADE OF PLASTIC.  THIS EXPRESS ENVELOPE BECAME JAMMED IN BETWEEN THE TWO RUNNING BELTS.  THE RUNNING OF THE BELTS DETERIORATED THE INTEGRITY OF THE AEROSOL CAN RELEASING ITS CONTENTS.  ALSO, IN THE EXPRESS ENVELOPE WERE FIVE BOOKS. THERE WAS NO INDICATION ON THE PACKAGE THAT IT CONTAINED A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: (MTPL A) UNION PACIFIC TRAIN (PCHK1-11), DERAILED 18 CARS AT HOMLY, OREGON, MP 229, LAGRANDE SUBDIVISION, IDAHO AND COLUMBIA RIVER DIVISION. AS A RESULT OF DERAILMENT, THE 31ST THROUGH 48TH CARS WERE DERAILED. TANK CAR UTLX 13515 (35TH HEAD CAR) IMPACTED THE GROUND RESULTING IN 2 INCH PLUG INSTALLED BLIND FLANGE OVER INTERNAL BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE BEING TORN OFF. THIS RESULTED IN SMALL DRIP TYPE LEAK OUT OF BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. THE TWO INCH HOLE WAS PLUGGED WHILE CONTENTS OF TANK CAR WAS PUMPED INTO COMPATIBLE HIGHWAY CARGO TANK FOR DELIVERY TO CONSIGNEE. THE FOLLOWING AGENCIES WERE AT THE SCENE OF THE DERAILMENT: ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY, OREGON DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, REPRESENTATIVES OF CONFEDERATED TRIBES OF THE UMATILLA INDIAN RESERVATION, RALPH FORNEY, FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION, LARRY KJOLSETH, PURE GRO CHEMICAL CO., AND UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONSE PERSONNEL. (SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEAN L. WHITELEY.) (MTPL B) UNION PACIFIC TRAIN (PCHK1-11) DERAILED 18 CARS AT HOMLY, OR, MP 229, LAGRANDE SUBDIVISION, IDAHO AND COLUMBIA RIVER DIVISIONS. AS A RESULT, THE 31ST THROUGH THE 48TH CARS DERAILED. TANK CAR GATX 26088 (THE 39TH CAR) SUSTAINED A SMALL CRACK ON THE RIGHT SIDE, 18 INCHES FROM THE MANWAY. THE PRODUCT WAS REMOVED WITH PUMP INTO COMPATIBLE HIGHWAY CARGO TANK. TANK CAR GATX 52848 (38TH CAR) SUSTAINED LARGE PUNCTURE AND RIP ON THE LEFT SIDE LOWER PORTION WHICH RESULTED IN INSTANTANEOUS LOSS OF ENTIRE CONTENTS. SPILLED PRODUCT ENTERED DRY DITCH SOUTHSIDE OF MAINLINE AND FLOWED ONTO ADJACENT PASTURE LAND. CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED BY RIEDEL ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES AND SPREAD ON AREA FARM LAND WITH APPROVAL OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY. THE FOLLOWING AGENCIES WERE AT THE SCENE OF THE DERAILMENT: EPA, OREGON DEQ, REPRESENTATIVES OF CONFEDERATED TRIBES UMATILLA INDIAN RESERVATION, RALPH FORNEY, (FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION), LARRY KJOLSETH, PURE GRO CHEMICAL CO., AND UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE PERSONNEL. (SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DEAN WHITELEY)

(SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEAN L. WHITELEY.) (MTPL B) UNION PACIFIC TRAIN (PCHK1-11) DERAILED 18 CARS AT HOMLY, OR, MP 229, LAGRANDE SUBDIVISION, IDAHO AND COLUMBIA RIVER DIVISIONS. AS A RESULT, THE 31ST THROUGH THE 48TH CARS DERAILED. TANK CAR GATX 26088 (THE 39TH CAR) SUSTAINED A SMALL CRACK ON THE RIGHT SIDE, 18 INCHES FROM THE MANWAY. THE PRODUCT WAS REMOVED WITH PUMP INTO COMPATIBLE HIGHWAY CARGO TANK. TANK CAR GATX 52848 (38TH CAR) SUSTAINED LARGE PUNCTURE AND RIP ON THE LEFT SIDE LOWER PORTION WHICH RESULTED IN INSTANTANEOUS LOSS OF ENTIRE CONTENTS. SPILLED PRODUCT ENTERED DRY DITCH SOUTHSIDE OF MAINLINE AND FLOWED ONTO ADJACENT PASTURE LAND. CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED BY RIEDEL ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES AND SPREAD ON AREA FARM LAND WITH APPROVAL OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY. THE FOLLOWING AGENCIES WERE AT THE SCENE OF THE DERAILMENT: EPA, OREGON DEQ, REPRESENTATIVES OF CONFEDERATED TRIBES UMATILLA INDIAN RESERVATION, RALPH FORNEY, (FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION), LARRY KJOLSETH, PURE GRO CHEMICAL CO., AND UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE PERSONNEL. (SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DEAN WHITELEY)

column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) T.H. SMITH WAS NOTIFIED FROM THE UPTL IN LAREDO, TX THAT XTRZ 256292 WAS FOUND BY THE BROKER TO HAVE A LEAKING DRUM DURING OFF-LOADING.  THE BROKER, ZUGINA, CONTINUED TO OFF-LOAD, AND PATCHED, REPAIRED AND OVERPACKED THE LEAKING DRUM.  THE CARGO WAS THEN LOADED ON A TRAILER FOR TRANSPORT TO MEXICO OVER THE ROAD.

HOLMAN TRANSFER WAREHOUSE FORCES WERE PREPARING MP 254781 FOR UNLOADING AND NOTED LADING STACKED ON PALLETS WHICH WERE SHRINK WRAPPED HAD SHIFTED DURING TRANSPORTATION AND INSPECTION DETERMINED 29 BAGS WERE DAMAGED. ALL 29 BAGS WERE PLACED IN RECOVER DRUMS AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER. OS&D REPORT WAS COMPLETED ON 04/02/91. PORTLAND OFFICE POLICE/HAZMAT DEPT WAS NOT NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT. ACCOUNTS SUPV LESLIE LACROSS, HOLMAN TRANSFER, PORTLAND, WAS CONTACTED FOR RECORDS COVERING BOXCAR.

WHEN FRICK DRIVER (WILLIAM STOUDER) FINISHED UNLOADING AT NORAM CHEMICAL, HE RELEASED THE PRODUCT THAT WAS IN HIS HOSE (APROX. 1-2 GALLONS) INTO NORAMS DIKED CONTAINMENT PIT INSTEAD OF GETTING A CONTAINER TO CATCH THIS PRODUCT.  WHEN THE SHIFT SUPERVISOR WAS CALLED HE INSTRUCTED HIS MEN TO COVER THE WETTED AREA WITH "FLOOR DRY". WILLIAM STOUDER WAS INSTRUCTED TO COME IN TO THE HOME OFFICE WHERE HE WAS GIVEN HIS ONE AND ONLY WARNING THAT HIS BEHAVIOR WOULD NOT BE TOLERATED.
